Avoid combining multiple already 'framed' items or items with 'ruined frames' as this frequently leads to 'overcomplicated' items with severely negative values.

message: Focus on framing! Combine two ingredients first, then use the frame tool on the *combined* ingredient. The highest values come from combining a 'natural, soft' ingredient with an 'artificial, hard' one (this mix is often worth 30, and 50 when framed). Combining two 'soft' ingredients (artificial or natural) usually yields a 0-value mix, then 20 when framed. NEVER combine two already framed items; they will be ruined and result in negative value. Be cautious with scissors; they often ruin framed items. It's safer to submit with 50 points than to risk creating negative items.

message: Focus on creating two separate lines of items: one purely artificial and one purely natural. The pattern that worked best for me was: combine two ingredients of the same type (e.g., two natural items OR two artificial items) -> use scissors on the combined item -> use the frame tool on the cut item. Never combine two already framed items; this consistently leads to 'overcomplicated' items with 'ruined frames' and very negative values. Be cautious with scissors on 'overcomplicated' or already framed items, as it often makes them worse. Aim to get items to 50+ value before considering submitting, but don't risk a good score on a speculative combination.

message: The best strategy is to use 'scissors' on a *soft* ingredient (like sponge, feather, or sunflower). This will yield a valuable 'cut' item (e.g., +25). Immediately follow by using the 'frame' tool on that 'cut' item to create a high-value item (e.g., +45). Avoid combining multiple items or using tools on items that already have a 'ruined frame' feature, as this almost always leads to significantly negative values. Using 'scissors' on *hard* ingredients also tends to result in negative values.
